<h1>From Lieutenant Colonel Joseph Reed</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">My dear General</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Philad. March 3. 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I have not been favoured with any Thing from you since my too last<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> but that never makes any Difference in my Writing as your Claims of Friendship &amp; Gratitude upon me are superior to all other. The Congress have made an Appointment of Generals as by the inclosed Paper.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Armstrong is ordered to South CarolinaThompson to New York the others keep their present Situation. Genl Lees Destination is changed to Virginia from undoubted Authority that it will be a principal Scene of ActionThe Congress have acceded to the Proposition respecting myself so that unless some new Event unforeseen &amp; very important should happen I shall be with you this Summer.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> I must beg your Indulgence till I can get my Family into some convenient Situation &amp; settle my AffairsIn the mean Time I am forwarding your Camp Equipage which I have extended in many small particulars beyond your OrderArnold is to be intrusted with the Affairs of CanadaWooster having either resigned or been superseded<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> I know not whichMelchior is come from Quebeck in 12 Days where he left our little Army now strengthned to 1500 Men in good Spirits &amp; Still pleasing themselves with the Hopes of being Masters of the Town I have not yet seen him so that I can give you no farther particularsBut I understand they are like to want battering Cannons &amp; Mortars<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0005-ptr">5</a>No Arrivals of Powder or Arms since my last; or any Account of our Fleettho from their present cruizing Ground we hope they will fall in with Ld Cornwallis &amp; the Transports.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
<p>Notwithstanding the Act of Parliament for seizing our Property &amp; a thousand other Proofs of a bitter &amp; irreconciliable Spiritthere is a strange Reluctance in the Minds of many to cut the Knot which ties us to Great Brittain particularly in this Colony &amp; to the SouthwardTho no Man of Understanding expects any Good from the Commissioners, yet they are for waiting to hear their Proposals before they declare off<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0007" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0007-ptr">7</a>However yesterday I was informed Letters had been sent to France to know what Encouragement we might expect from that Quarter.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0008" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0008-ptr">8</a> Our Coast is yet clear, it is a golden Opportunity to make Provision for the War which I hope will not be lost. If the other
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0407">[407]</span>
Provinces had done any Thing like this in the making of Arms this Winter we should have been tolerably providedWe shall by the 1st April have made 4000 Stand since last October every Part done hereWe are casting Cannon &amp; there is more Salt Petre made than in all the Provinces put together. Six Powder Mills are erecting in different Partsthe two near this City del[i]ver 2500 lb. <img class="char" src="images/char-per-trans.png" alt="[per]"/> Week &amp; are now in very good Order. Many, many Attempts have been made to get a Bounty for the New England Troops but without EffectThe Congress are resolved that you shall abandon the Lines &amp; give up their Country to be ravaged if they will not defend it upon the same Terms as those inlisted here (such as march to Canada only excepted). The Assembly have it under Consideration to raise 2000 Men for the Defence of this Province, but I doubt its taking[.] perhaps there may be half the Number.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0009" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0009-ptr">9</a> I am told we can easily raise 2 or 3 more Battalions if we had Arms &amp;c. for them. I do not think I shall bring any Person with me when I come. Mr Webb has long had an Inclination to be in your Family if the Post should be agreeable to him &amp; he is agreeable to you I believe I should prefer him to any other.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0010" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0010-ptr">10</a></p>
<p>The Post is just going so that I have only Time to add that I am my dear Sir Yours most Affecte</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">J. Reed</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>These letters have not been identified.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>This enclosure has not been identified. For the appointment of the brigadier generals, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0296&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0296-fn-0001#GEWN-03-03-02-0296-fn-0001" class="document">Charles Lee to GW, this date, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Congress resolved on 1 Mar. that an addition of 34 dollars per month be added to the pay of Joseph Reed, Esqr. the secretary to General Washington, on account of the extraordinary services at present attending that office, by reason of the Generals direction of the naval department (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:180).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Congress promoted John Thomas to major general on 6 Mar. and gave him command of the forces in Canada (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:186).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>For Isaac Melchers activities in Philadelphia, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0284&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0284-fn-0003#GEWN-03-03-02-0284-fn-0003" class="document">Charles Lee to GW, 29 Feb. 1776, n.3</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>Charles Cornwallis, second Earl Cornwallis (17381805), who had been promoted to major general in the British army effective 29 Sept. 1775, sailed from Cork, Ireland, in February with 2,500 troops to meet Gen. Henry Clinton at Cape Fear, North Carolina. The troops were to participate in Clintons expedition against the southern colonies, but Cornwallis played little part in it.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>For a discussion of the Prohibitory Act and the peace commissioners, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0274&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0274-fn-0019#GEWN-03-03-02-0274-fn-0019" class="document">GW to Reed, 26 Feb.9 Mar. 1776, n.19</a>.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0408">[408]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>On 2 Mar. Congresss committee of secret correspondence authorized Silas Deane to go to France in order to purchase clothing and military stores for the army and to explore the possibilities of diplomatic relations and a commercial or military alliance with the French. See the committees minutes of proceedings for that date in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Paul H. Smith et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Letters of Delegates to Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;. 26 vols. Washington, D.C., 19762000. ]">Smith, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Delegates</span></span>, 3:32023.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>On 1 Mar. the Pennsylvania general assembly received a petition dated 22 Feb. from the Pennsylvania committee of safety requesting that 2,000 men be raised for the defense of the colony. Five days later the assembly authorized the raising of 1,500 men who were to be organized into two rifle battalions and one musket battalion, each battalion consisting of 500 men (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Samuel Hazard et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Pennsylvania Archives&lt;/i&gt;. 9 ser., 138 vols. Philadelphia and Harrisburg, 18521949. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Pa. Archives</span></span>, 8th ser., 8:742526, 742933).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0297-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>Samuel Blachley Webb, who was an aide-de-camp to Gen. Israel Putnam at this time, became one of GWs aides-de-camp on 21 June 1776.</p>

</div>
</div>
